payload.text:
To fix our charting platform not fully using the page, Here’s how to fix it step by step:


---

1️⃣ Ensure the page wrapper fills the viewport

In your page, wrap the chart in a div like this:

export default function ChartPage() {
  return (
    <div style={{ width: "100vw", height: "100vh" }}>
      <TradingViewChartEnhanced />
    </div>
  );
}

100vw → full width of the viewport

100vh → full height of the viewport


This ensures the chart component can expand to fill the whole screen.


---

2️⃣ Ensure the chart itself is 100% height

In your TradingViewChartEnhanced.jsx, make sure the chart div is also 100% height:

<div
  id="tradingview_chart"
  ref={chartRef}
  style={{ width: "100%", height: "100%" }}
/>

Also, make sure the parent container div of your controls + chart fills the height:

<div style={{ width: "100%", height: "100%" }}>
  {/* Controls */}
  <div style={{ marginBottom: "10px" }}>
    ...
  </div>

  {/* Chart */}
  <div
    id="tradingview_chart"
    ref={chartRef}
    style={{ width: "100%", height: "calc(100% - 50px)" }} // subtract control bar height
  />
</div>

calc(100% - 50px) adjusts for the height of the control bar (dropdowns/buttons)

This makes the chart take the rest of the page



---

3️⃣ Optional: Make body & html full height

Sometimes Vite projects don’t have full-page height by default. In your index.css (or global CSS), add:

html, body, #root {
  height: 100%;
  margin: 0;
  padding: 0;
}

This ensures 100% viewport height is available to your React page.


---

